<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 41 companion (The Draft That Looks Like a Deliverable — the Part XII umbrella). The
    chapter's stance is that AI-generated code is a draft, not a deliverable: it goes through the same
    quality gate as human code, plus a few AI-specific checks. This module shows that stance in code on
    the storefront domain, in two demonstrations.

    (a) An AI-drafted customer lookup that builds its SQL by string concatenation — the
    vulnerability-inheritance pattern the chapter describes, reproduced from the insecure examples that
    are well-represented in public training data. It is the same OWASP A03 / CWE-89 injection class the
    Chapter 30 module covers, here framed as an AI draft. The reviewed fix passes the value as a bound
    PreparedStatement parameter. The AiReviewGate running path is wired to the reviewed fix alone; the
    AI-drafted shape is never reachable from it and exists only so a test can prove the defect.

    (b) An AI test generated FROM the implementation that reaches full line coverage while asserting
    almost nothing, so the boundary and arithmetic mutants on the code under test survive — the
    tests-from-code trap (the test pins current behavior, bugs included, instead of independently
    encoding intended behavior). Beside it, a spec-derived test encodes the intended behavior from the
    requirement and kills those mutants. Mutation testing (Chapter 23) is the check that exposes the
    hollow test; this module demonstrates the contrast with tests and prose, the way the Chapter 23
    module does, rather than wiring a mutation-testing plugin into this build.

    Every AI statistic in the chapter prose is a dated, attributed snapshot; none is embedded here,
    because a statistic baked into code would silently go stale. The code demonstrates the structural
    mechanisms (which do not date), not the figures (which do).

    Runtime dependencies are JDK-only; the one extra GAV is the SpotBugs annotations artifact, on the
    compile path only. The module dogfoods the book: every shape is held to the same `quality` gate the
    chapter describes, and the build is green.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>ai-generated-code-quality</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 41 — The Draft That Looks Like a Deliverable (ai-generated-code-quality)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      SpotBugs annotations (SOURCE-PIN.md: SpotBugs 4.10.2 line; this module builds against the locally
      cached 4.9.3 engine the companion code is pinned to, so the annotations track that engine). The
      single version literal here is the one pinned GAV available for a per-site
      @SuppressFBWarnings(value, justification) — not a BOM or version-set. The annotations are
      CLASS-retained, so `provided` scope keeps them on the compile path only and the module's runtime
      stays JDK-only like the rest of the companion code.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
      <artifactId>spotbugs-annotations</artifactId>
      <version>4.9.3</version>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    Static-analysis rule gates from Chapter 16, opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays
    fast. The maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine (Checkstyle 9.3); we override it to
    the pinned engine via a plugin-level dependency — the "two-pin" lesson (the build plugin and the
    analyzer engine are separate versions). This module is a direct child of the companion-code root,
    which pins no quality profile of its own, so the profile is declared here (the same shape the
    Chapter 30 module uses) and reads the config under this module's config/ dir.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point (Chapter 16) — complementary to Checkstyle's source
            view. This module ships one deliberate counter-example — the AI-drafted string-concatenated
            query — which core SpotBugs raises at this threshold; it carries a single narrowly-scoped,
            reasoned suppression in the exclude filter (the chapter's "suppress with a documented
            reason, never disable a detector" discipline). That finding firing on AI-drafted code is the
            chapter's thesis in the build: the gate does not care who wrote the code.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
